  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_137112781" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/137112781" />
    <a title="Richard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4469938-richard"><img alt="Richard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1289221723p2/4469938.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/137112781?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard" href="/user/show/4469938-richard">Richard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer137112781" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17264038142890160442">I&apos;m confused - is Picoult considered a writer of young adult fiction? This is the first one of her books that I&apos;ve read and am quite surprised at how shallow it all was. Lazy plotting, superficial characters and courtroom shenanigans all contribute to a tale that&apos;s neither believable nor very engaging.<br/><br/>Teenage Katie is an Amish woman accused of suffocating her infant immediately after giving birth to it. Lawyer Ellie just happens to be in the area, reluctantly takes on the case and is forced to l</span>
  <span id="freeText17264038142890160442" style="display:none">I'm confused - is Picoult considered a writer of young adult fiction? This is the first one of her books that I've read and am quite surprised at how shallow it all was. Lazy plotting, superficial characters and courtroom shenanigans all contribute to a tale that's neither believable nor very engaging.<br /><br />Teenage Katie is an Amish woman accused of suffocating her infant immediately after giving birth to it. Lawyer Ellie just happens to be in the area, reluctantly takes on the case and is forced to live with Katie and her family on their Amish farm for the duration of the trial. This setup is as preposterous as it sounds but at least we don't get any comical scenes of Ellie being awaken at 4am by a rooster or forced to milk a cow. **eye roll**<br /><br />Ellie is allowed to break strict Amish traditions when it suits the story. She's allowed to attend closed confessional meetings and bring electricity onto the farm to run her laptop. Ellie's boyfriend, Coop, is also welcomed into Katie's household without much fuss, frequently lets himself into their house without knocking and becomes a regular at dinnertime. At one point, both Coop and Ellie's ex-boyfriend join the family for supper. This is all hard to take seriously after its made clear how little use the Amish have for outsiders in general and the legal system outside their own community and surprising, considering that Katie's father didn't want to hire a lawyer at all.<br /><br />None of the characters here behave in a believable fashion and only seem motivated by the stereotypes assigned to them and what the plot requires them to do in order for Picoult to lurch the story forward. No one here is bound by the laws of either real life or the legal system. All throughout the trial, Ellie sleeps with a psychiatrist she brings in to first to evaluate Katie and then ultimately use as a witness in the courtroom. The prosecuter actually questions their relationship at one point but its dropped quickly and quietly without any consequence to anyone at all.<br /><br />Katie lies throughout almost the entire book. For the longest time, Katie denies having any memory of the night of the murder and in fact, only admits to having given birth in the first place when overwhelming forensic evidence is supplied. At first, her bold-faced denials spark our interest and we wonder if she is delusional and perhaps quite capable of murder. But no, she's just a stressed out girl afraid of losing her family's approval. At a late point in the story, Katie begs Ellies not to take the easy way out with a claim of temporary insanity. I suppose this is meant to be the heart of the novel where the inexperienced country girl remind the cynical big city lawyer what's really important, ie THE TRUTH. But Katie's been such an unreliable source of information and has changed her story so many times that this scene has no weight.<br /><br />This general sloppiness runs throughout the entire novel. Katie and Ellie share a room during most of the book and one is always sneaking outside in the middle of the night to meet someone. Sometimes one is awakened by the other's less than stealthy tactics, sometimes not. At no point do any other family members hear these comings and goings, not because its explained in a realistic manner but simply because the plot doesn't want them intruding. In another instance, Katie's friend spends the day outside with her while wearing rollerblades, which made me wonder just how much asphalt or pavement does a rural Amish farm in Lancaster, PA sport? Conveniently, freshly single Ellie encounters an old flame recently divorced and wouldn't you know it, he's never stopped loving her? And on and on...<br /><br />Nothing here is remotely believable and with the characters only painted with the broadest of strokes, this novel comes out an epic fail in my book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17264038142890160442" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

